## Template fields (high level)

The authoritative mapping/aliases live in Storeapp `masive-upload/utils/processCsvData.js`, but at a minimum the backend consumer requires (per product):

- `name`
- `type` (`Product` / `Service`)
- `description`
- `units`
- `categoryID` (UUID or category name)
- For `type === "Product"`: `measurementUnitGroupID`
- At least one `variant` with `defaultPrice > 0`

If your generated XLSX uses different headers, the Storeapp parser may not map them correctly and the backend will fail validation.

## Run generator (presets / CLI)

The generator supports running **one scenario at a time** via CLI.

List presets:
```
python3 main.py
```

Run a preset:
```
python3 main.py --preset 1000_mixed_ok
python3 main.py --preset 1000_mixed_err1
python3 main.py --preset 1000_1prop_ok
python3 main.py --preset 1000_1prop_err_random
python3 main.py --preset 1000_2props_ok
python3 main.py --preset 1000_2props_err_random
python3 main.py --preset 5000_mixed_err1
python3 main.py --preset 10000_mixed_ok
python3 main.py --preset 10000_mixed_err5
```

Run a custom scenario (overrides preset values if provided):
```
python3 main.py \
  --filename tech_custom_10000_err2.xlsx \
  --product-count 10000 \
  --variants-per-product 2 \
  --inject-errors \
  --error-rate 0.02 \
  --seed 7
```

Disable error injection explicitly:
```
python3 main.py --preset 10000_mixed_err5 --no-inject-errors
```

Notes:

- The current generator creates a **mixed** file: a small number of products with variants + the rest as simple products.
- Because of that, total rows can be **slightly higher than** `product_count`.

## Generated Excel Headers (Row 5)

The `main.py` script generates the following headers that match the frontend `processCsvData.js` keyMapping:

The template supports **1 attribute** (only `Attribute color`) or **2 attributes** (`Attribute color` + `Attribute material`) depending on `--attribute-count` / preset.

| Column | Header | Description |
|--------|--------|-------------|
| A | `Type*` | Product/Service |
| B | `Name*` | Product name |
| C | `Fotografía producto` | Photo URL (optional) |
| D | `Category*` | Category name |
| E | `Grupo de Unidades` | Unit group name |
| F | `Unit*` | Unit name |
| G | `Description*` | Description |
| H | `isPerishable*` | Yes/No |
| I | `Attribute color` | Color attribute value |
| J | `Attribute material` | Material attribute value |
| K | `SKU` | SKU code |
| L | `Barcode` | Primary barcode |
| M | `Código 2` | Secondary barcode |
| N | `Código 3` | Tertiary barcode |
| O | `Cost` | Cost value |
| P | `Price*` | Price value |
| Q | `Base (Unidad)` | PUM base unit |
| R | `Valor` | PUM value |
| S | `Proveedor` | Vendor name |
| T | `Costo Proveedor` | Vendor cost |

**Note:** Attribute columns must be prefixed with `Attribute ` (e.g., `Attribute color`) for the frontend parser to recognize them as attributes.

### 1-attribute mode (attribute_count=1)

| Column | Header |
|--------|--------|
| A | `Type*` |
| B | `Name*` |
| C | `Fotografía producto` |
| D | `Category*` |
| E | `Grupo de Unidades` |
| F | `Unit*` |
| G | `Description*` |
| H | `isPerishable*` |
| I | `Attribute color` |
| J | `SKU` |
| K | `Barcode` |
| L | `Código 2` |
| M | `Código 3` |
| N | `Cost` |
| O | `Price*` |
| P | `Base (Unidad)` |
| Q | `Valor` |
| R | `Proveedor` |
| S | `Costo Proveedor` |

## Duplicate Product Names (NEW!)

The backend now supports **merging duplicate product names as variants**:

- If multiple rows have the same product name, they are merged into a single product with multiple variants
- **Requirement:** ALL rows with the same name MUST have variants (attributes + SKU/price)
- If any duplicate row is missing variants, the backend will return an error

Example:
```
Row 2: iPhone 28 | color=blanco | SKU=IP28-W | Price=1000
Row 5: iPhone 28 | color=rojo   | SKU=IP28-R | Price=1100
```
Result: 1 product "iPhone 28" with 2 variants (blanco, rojo)
